# Using Cursor Rules in CitrusRules

## Accessing Existing Rules
- Cursor rules provide contextual guidance for this project
- View rules in the `.cursor/rules/` directory
- Rules apply automatically based on their metadata:
  - `alwaysApply: true` - Applied to all contexts
  - `globs: ["**/*.js"]` - Applied to matching files
  - Others can be referenced directly with `@ruleName`

## Creating New Rules
1. Create a new `.mdc` file in the `.cursor/rules/` directory
2. Include the required YAML frontmatter section at the top:
   ```yaml
   ---
   description: Brief description of the rule
   globs: ["**/*.js"]  # Optional - files this applies to
   alwaysApply: false  # Optional - whether to always apply
   ---
   ```
3. Write your rule content in Markdown format
4. Reference project files using: `[filename.js](mdc:filename.js)`

## Using CitrusRules to Add Templates
- Run:
  ```bash
  npx citrusrules --feature --agent
  ```
- This will fetch predefined templates from the GitHub repository 
- Templates are fetched from: [src/config.js](mdc:src/config.js)
- New templates require adding new flags to [bin/cli.js](mdc:bin/cli.js)
